    faqs: [
      { question: 'Is OSHA 10 or OSHA 30 better for my resume?', answer: 'OSHA 30-hour training is more comprehensive and preferred for supervisory and management roles. OSHA 10-hour is the baseline requirement for most construction workers. If you hold both, list them both. Many employers and projects require OSHA 30 as a minimum for foremen and site supervisors. Some states like New York and Connecticut mandate OSHA training by law.' },
      { question: 'How do I describe OSHA compliance experience on my resume?', answer: 'Focus on measurable outcomes: days without incidents, reduction in injury rates (TRIR), EMR improvements, and number of inspections conducted. Describe specific programs you developed or managed, such as fall protection plans, hazard communication programs, or confined space procedures. Mention your role in incident investigations and corrective action implementation.' },
      { question: 'Does OSHA compliance experience help in non-construction industries?', answer: 'Yes, OSHA standards apply to virtually every industry. Manufacturing, warehousing, energy, healthcare, and agriculture all have specific OSHA requirements. The principles of hazard identification, risk assessment, and safety program management transfer across industries. OSHA compliance expertise positions you for safety manager and EHS director roles in any sector.' }
    ]
