    faqs: [
      { question: 'How do I describe safety protocol experience without a safety-specific job title?', answer: 'Focus on the safety responsibilities you held within your regular role. This includes leading toolbox talks, conducting pre-task JHAs, performing safety inspections, mentoring new workers on safe practices, and participating in incident investigations. Many trades and supervisory positions have significant safety components even without a formal safety title.' },
      { question: 'What safety certifications complement my trades experience?', answer: 'The OSHA 30-hour course is the most widely recognized baseline. The Board of Certified Safety Professionals offers the Construction Health and Safety Technician (CHST) and Safety Trained Supervisor (STS-C) designations specifically for field personnel. First Aid/CPR/AED certification is universally valuable. HAZWOPER 40-hour training is required for hazardous waste site work.' },
      { question: 'Are safety protocol skills relevant for non-supervisory positions?', answer: 'Yes. Employers value workers at every level who demonstrate safety awareness and compliance. Listing safety skills shows that you understand proper procedures, will follow PPE requirements, and contribute to a safe work environment. Workers who actively participate in safety programs are more likely to be promoted to lead and supervisory roles.' }
    ]
